\pard\qc\sb240\sa240{\b\fs32 Weekend Python Crash Course \u128013?}\par
\pard\qc\sb120\sa240{\fs24 Day 1: Lab Sheet \u8211? Python Basics & Core Concepts}\par

\pard\sb240\sa120{\b\cf1\fs28 \u127937? Exercise 1: Hello Python}\par

\pard\sb60\sa30
1. Open your IDE or Python REPL.\par
2. Create a new file called hello.py.\par
3. Write a Python program that:\par
\pard\fi-360\li1080\sb30
\u8226?\tab Prints your name.\par
\u8226?\tab Prints your age.\par
\u8226?\tab Prints a welcome message.\par

\pard\sb120\sa60{\b Example Output:}\par
\pard\sb60{\f1\fs20
Hello, Alice!\par
You are 25 years old.\par
Welcome to Python!\par
}

\pard\sb240\sa120{\b\cf1\fs28 \u128290? Exercise 2: Variables and Data Types}\par

\pard\sb60\sa30
1. Create variables for:\par
\pard\fi-360\li1080\sb30
\u8226?\tab your_name (string)\par
\u8226?\tab your_age (integer)\par
\u8226?\tab favorite_number (float)\par

\pard\sb60\sa30
2. Print each variable on a new line.\par

\pard\sb120\sa60{\b\cf3 Bonus:} Print a sentence using all three variables, e.g.,\par
\pard\sb60{\f1\fs20
Alice is 25 years old and her favorite number is 7.5\par
}

\pard\sb240\sa120{\b\cf1\fs28 \u10133? Exercise 3: Basic Operators}\par

\pard\sb60\sa30
1. Assign values to variables a = 10 and b = 3.\par
2. Print the results of:\par
\pard\fi-360\li1080\sb30
\u8226?\tab Addition\par
\u8226?\tab Subtraction\par
\u8226?\tab Multiplication\par
\u8226?\tab Division\par
\u8226?\tab Modulus\par

\pard\sb60\sa30
3. Extra challenge: Calculate the area of a rectangle with width = 5 and height = 7.\par

\page

\pard\sb240\sa120{\b\cf1\fs28 \u128739? Exercise 4: Input and Output}\par

\pard\sb60\sa30
1. Ask the user for their {\b name} using input().\par
2. Ask the user for their {\b age}.\par
3. Print a greeting message that includes their name and age.\par

\pard\sb120\sa60{\b\cf3 Bonus:} Ask the user for {\b two numbers} and print their {\b sum, difference, product, and quotient}.\par

\pard\sb240\sa120{\b\cf1\fs28 \u128256? Exercise 5: Control Flow \u8211? If/Else}\par

\pard\sb60\sa30
1. Ask the user for a number.\par
2. Print whether the number is {\b positive, negative, or zero}.\par

\pard\sb120\sa60{\b\cf3 Bonus:} Ask the user for their age and print:\par
\pard\fi-360\li1080\sb30
\u8226?\tab "Child" if age < 12\par
\u8226?\tab "Teen" if 12 <= age < 18\par
\u8226?\tab "Adult" if age >= 18\par

\pard\sb240\sa120{\b\cf1\fs28 \u128256? Exercise 6: Loops}\par

\pard\sb120\sa60{\b\fs22 Part A \u8211? For Loop}\par
\pard\sb60\sa30
1. Print all numbers from 1 to 10.\par
2. Print all even numbers from 2 to 20.\par

\pard\sb120\sa60{\b\fs22 Part B \u8211? While Loop}\par
\pard\sb60\sa30
1. Initialize a variable count = 0.\par
2. Print the value of count while count < 5, and increment count each time.\par

\pard\sb120\sa60{\b\cf3 Bonus:} Write a number guessing game:\par
\pard\fi-360\li1080\sb30
\u8226?\tab Program selects a random number between 1\u8211?10.\par
\u8226?\tab User keeps guessing until they find the correct number.\par

\pard\sb60\sa30{\i Hint: Use import random and random.randint(1,10).}\par

\page

\pard\sb240\sa120{\b\cf1\fs28 \u9989? End-of-Day Mini Project}\par

\pard\sb60\sa30
Create a program that:\par

\pard\sb60\sa30
1. Asks the user for:\par
\pard\fi-360\li1080\sb30
\u8226?\tab Name\par
\u8226?\tab Age\par
\u8226?\tab Favorite number\par

\pard\sb60\sa30
2. Prints:\par
\pard\sb60{\f1\fs20
Hello <name>! In 5 years, you will be <age+5>.\par
Your favorite number doubled is <favorite_number*2>.\par
}

\pard\sb60\sa30
3. Extra challenge: Repeat the program for {\b 3 users} using a loop.\par

\pard\sb240\sa120{\b\cf1\fs28 \u128161? Tips}\par

\pard\fi-360\li720\sb60
\u8226?\tab Test each part of your code as you go.\par
\u8226?\tab Use comments to explain your logic:\par

\pard\sb60{\f1\fs20
# This prints a greeting\par
print("Hello, world!")\par
}

\pard\fi-360\li720\sb60
\u8226?\tab Save your file often.\par
\u8226?\tab Don't be afraid to make mistakes \u8212? debugging helps you learn.\par

